---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { SITE } from "../../config/site";
import { amortizationSchedule } from "../../lib/calc/loan";

const title = "Calculate Mortgage Payoff with Additional Principal Payments";
const description =
  "A practical way to estimate how additional principal payments change payoff time and total interest, plus what to confirm with your lender. Educational use only.";

const examplePrincipal = 300000;
const exampleApr = 6.5;
const exampleTermMonths = 360;
const exampleExtraMonthly = 250;
const base = amortizationSchedule({ principal: examplePrincipal, aprPercent: exampleApr, termMonths: exampleTermMonths });
const withExtra = amortizationSchedule({
  principal: examplePrincipal,
  aprPercent: exampleApr,
  termMonths: exampleTermMonths,
  extraMonthly: exampleExtraMonthly
});
const money0 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
const pct2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/guides/calculate-mortgage-payoff-with-additional-principal-payments"
>
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Calculate payoff with additional principal</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>Calculate mortgage payoff with additional principal payments</h1>
    <p>
      Additional principal payments reduce the loan balance sooner. That usually reduces total interest and can move your payoff date
      earlier. This guide shows a simple workflow to estimate the impact and avoid common lender posting pitfalls.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/mortgage-payoff">Mortgage payoff topic hub</a>
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Extra principal calculator</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/principal-only-extra-payments">Principal-only checklist</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">The workflow (simple and reliable)</h2>
    <ol class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Compute your baseline principal-and-interest payment in the <a href="/calculators/mortgage-payment-calculator">Mortgage Payment Calculator</a>.</li>
      <li>Check the baseline amortization table in the <a href="/calculators/amortization-schedule-calculator">Amortization Schedule Calculator</a>.</li>
      <li>Model additional principal payments in the <a href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Extra Payment Mortgage Calculator</a>.</li>
      <li>Compare payoff date and total interest between baseline vs extra payment scenarios.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Inputs to gather first</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Current balance:</strong> use the statement balance, not just the original loan amount.</li>
      <li><strong>Interest rate:</strong> the current APR on your note.</li>
      <li><strong>Remaining term:</strong> years/months left on the loan.</li>
      <li><strong>Extra payment plan:</strong> monthly extra, lump sum, or both.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Using the correct remaining balance and term makes a big difference. If you are mid-loan, do not use the original balance unless you
      adjust the term accordingly.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Monthly extra vs lump sum</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
        Earlier principal reduction tends to save more interest because it reduces the balance sooner. A smaller monthly extra can beat a
        larger lump sum that happens later.
      </p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
        Common comparisons: $100-$300 extra each month vs one extra payment per year vs a one-time lump sum.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">What usually does not change</h2>
      <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Your required monthly payment usually stays the same (unless you recast).</li>
        <li>Escrow (tax/insurance) is separate from principal and interest.</li>
        <li>Exact payoff month can vary due to posting dates and rounding.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Common mistakes to avoid</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Using the original loan balance when you are years into the loan.</li>
      <li>Comparing scenarios with different terms or rates.</li>
      <li>Assuming your extra payment reduces escrow.</li>
      <li>Not verifying how the servicer applies the extra payment.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">A simple starter plan</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If you are unsure where to start, try three scenarios: $100 extra, $200 extra, and $300 extra per month. Compare the payoff dates and
      total interest for each option. Choose the largest amount you can consistently maintain without stressing your monthly cash flow.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Worked example (computed)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example: {money0.format(examplePrincipal)} at {pct2.format(exampleApr)}% APR for {exampleTermMonths} months. Compare baseline to adding
      {money0.format(exampleExtraMonthly)}/month in extra principal.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th class="num">Extra principal</th>
            <th class="num">Payoff time</th>
            <th class="num">Total interest</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(0)}</td>
            <td class="num">{base.months} months</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(base.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>With extra</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(exampleExtraMonthly)}</td>
            <td class="num">{withExtra.months} months</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(withExtra.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      In this example, extra payments save about {money0.format(Math.max(0, base.totalInterest - withExtra.totalInterest))} in interest and
      shorten payoff by {Math.max(0, base.months - withExtra.months)} months.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What to confirm with your lender</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>The additional amount is applied as <strong>principal-only</strong> (not "paid ahead" toward the next due date).</li>
      <li>There is no prepayment penalty (many loans have none; some do).</li>
      <li>If you want a lower required payment later, whether a recast is available and what it costs.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: a reliable payoff comparison</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Keep the baseline constant:</strong> same rate, term, and starting balance.</li>
      <li><strong>Change one variable at a time:</strong> monthly extra, lump sum, or timing.</li>
      <li><strong>Verify posting:</strong> check statements to confirm principal-only application.</li>
      <li><strong>Include liquidity:</strong> don't sacrifice emergency reserves for small gains.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Will extra principal lower my payment?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      Usually no. It shortens the term unless you recast or refinance.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Is a lump sum better than a monthly extra?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      Earlier is usually better for interest savings, but the best plan is the one you can sustain.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{" "}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/mortgages/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          Mortgages resources
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:10px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Run additional principal scenarios</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/amortization-with-extra-payments">Amortization with extra payments</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/one-extra-mortgage-payment-per-year">One extra payment per year</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Questions or corrections? Email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">
      Last updated: 2026-01-28
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
